ers and Singers Discuss Their Careers|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|isbn=978-1-4766-7022-5|year=2017|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|first=Claire|last=Folkard|title=Guinness World Records 2003|publisher=[[Guinness World Records]]|year=2002|isbn=978-1-892-05117-2|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/guinnessworldrec00folk}}\n*{{cite book|last=Fouz-Hern\u00e1ndez|first=Santiago|first2=Freya|last2=Jarman-Ivens|title=Madonna's Drowned Worlds|publisher=[[Ashgate Publishing, Ltd]]|isbn=978-0-7546-3372-3|year=2004|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/madonnasdrownedw0000unse}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Guilbert|first=Georges-Claude|title=Madonna as Postmodern Myth: How One Star's Self-Construction Rewrites Sex, Gender, Hollywood and the American Dream|authorlink=Georges Claude Guilbert|publisher=McFarland|year=2002|isbn=978-0-7864-1408-6|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Hawkins|first=Stan|title=Pop Music and Easy Listening|publisher=[[Routledge]]|isbn=978-0-7546-2952-8|year=2012|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Morton|first=Andrew|title=[[Madonna (book)|Madonna]]|year=2002|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers]]|isbn=978-0-312-98310-9|authorlink=Andrew Morton (writer)|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=O'Brien|first=Lucy|title=[[Madonna: Like an Icon]]|year=2008|authorlink=Lucy O'Brien|publisher=[[Bantam Press]]|isbn=978-0-552-15361-4|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Rooksby|first=Rikky|title=The Complete Guide to the Music of Madonna|year=2004|publisher=[[Music Sales Group|Omnibus Press]]|isbn=978-0-7119-9883-4|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/madonnacompleteg0000rook}}\n*{{cite book|last=Steiff|first=Josef|first2=Tristan|last2=Tamplin|title=Anime and Philosophy: Wide Eyed Wonder|publisher=Open Court|isbn=978-0-8126-9713-1|year=2010|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube|qYwgG2oyUbA|\"What It Feels Like for a Girl\" (music video)}}\n{{Madonna singles}}\n\n[[Category:2000 songs]]\n[[Category:2000s ballads]]\n[[Category:2001 singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Dance Club Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Madonna (entertainer) songs]]\n[[Category:Madonna (entertainer) video albums]]\n[[Category:Maverick Records singles]]\n[[Category:Music video controversies]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Spain]]\n[[Category:Songs with feminist themes]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Madonna (entertainer)]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Guy Sigsworth]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Spike Stent]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Madonna (entertainer)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Guy Sigsworth]]\n[[Category:Songs written by David Torn]]\n[[Category:Synth-pop ballads]]\n[[Category:Warner Records singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2001 single by Madonna}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name          = What It Feels Like for a Girl\n| cover         = Madonna - What it Feels Like for a Girl (single).png\n| alt           = Madonna wearing a white top with her tongue out to the camera. The photo is within a circular frame on top of which artist and song name is written in bold capital font.\n| border        = yes\n| caption       = Artwork for the US CD maxi single release\n| type          = single\n| artist        = [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]\n| album         = [[Music (Madonna album)|Music]]\n| B-side        = \"Lo Que Siente La Mujer\"\n| released      = {{start date|2001|04|16}}\n| format        = \n* [[CD single|CD]]\n* [[DVD single|DVD]]\n* [[Maxi single|maxi]]\n* [[cassette single|cassette]]\n* [[12-inch single|12-inch]]\n| recorded      = 2000\n| studio        = [[Sarm West Studios|Sarm West]] ([[London]])\n| genre         = \n* [[Electropop]]\n* [[synth-pop]]\n| length        = {{duration|m=04|s=43}}\n| label         = \n* [[Maverick Records|Maverick]]\n* [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n| writer        = \n* [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]\n* [[Guy Sigsworth]]\n* [[David Torn]]\n| producer      = \n* Madonna\n* Guy Sigsworth\n* [[Spike Stent|Mark \"Spike\" Stent]]\n| chronology    = Madonna singles\n| prev_title    = [[Don't Tell Me (Madonna song)|Don't Tell Me]]\n| prev_year     = 2000\n| next_title    = [[Die Another Day (song)|Die Another Day]]\n| next_year     = 2002\n| misc          =\n}}\n\"'''What It Feels Like for a Girl'''\" is a song recorded by American singer [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] for her eighth studio album ''[[Music (Madonna album)|Music]]'' (2000). It was released as the third and final single from the album on April 16, 2001, by [[Maverick Records]]. Madonna and [[Guy Sigsworth]] wrote and produced the song with [[David Torn]] as co-writer, and [[Spike Stent|Mark \"Spike\" Stent]] as a co-producer. \"What It Feels Like For a Girl\" is a mid-tempo [[electronic music|electronic]] and [[synth-pop]] song, with filtered bass licks, tidal keys and pads as part of its instrumentation. Lyrically, it conveys society's [[double standard]] toward women, addressing hurtful myths about female inferiority. To emphasize the message, the song opens with a spoken word sample by actress [[Charlotte Gainsbourg]] from the 1993 British film ''[[The Cement Garden (film)|The Cement Garden]]''. A Spanish version of the track, \"Lo Que Siente la Mujer\", was translated by Alberto Ferreras and included in the Latin American edition of ''Music''.\n\nThe song received acclaim from most music critics, who declared it as a highlight from the album, while also remarking it as one of the most mature musical ventures of Madonna's career. Commercially, \"What It Feels Like for a Girl\" reached the top-ten of the record charts in Australia, Canada, Denmark, Finland, Romania, Spain, Scotland and the United Kingdom. In the United States, it peaked at number 23 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and number-one on the [[Dance Club Songs]] chart.\n\nAn accompanying music video for the song was directed by Madonna's then-husband [[Guy Ritchie]] and premiered on March 22, 2001. It features the singer as a reckless woman on a crime spree. The video was criticized for its depiction of violence and abuse, which caused [[MTV]] to ban it before 9:00 pm. The single was also released on [[DVD single|DVD]] and became the highest weekly sales for a DVD release in the United States. Madonna performed the track on the promotional concerts for ''Music''  in November 2000 and on her 2001 [[Drowned World Tour]], where a remixed version was used as a video interlude and also performed in Spanish. The song was covered by [[List of Glee characters|the actors]] of television series [[Glee (TV series)|''Glee'']], during the episode \"[[The Power of Madonna]]\", and was included in the [[Glee: The Music, The Power of Madonna|accompanying EP]].\n\n==Background and development==\n[[File:Guy Sigsworth.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Guy Sigsworth]] (pictured in 2007), one of the main producers of \"What It Feels Like for a Girl\".|alt=Guy Sigsworth holding a white tea-cup in his right hand and smiling down.]]\nAfter the critical and commercial success of her seventh studio album, ''[[Ray of Light]]'' (1998), Madonna had intended to embark on a concert tour in September 1999, but the tour was cancelled due to the delay of her film ''[[The Next Best Thing]]'' (2000).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/512811/film-delay-blamed-for-madonna-tour-cancellation/|title=Film Delay Blamed For Madonna Tour Cancellation|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=March 15, 1999|accessdate=December 31, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222052013/http://www.mtv.com/news/512811/film-delay-blamed-for-madonna-tour-cancellation/|archivedate=December 22, 2017}}</ref> She released one-off singles like \"[[Beautiful Stranger]]\" (1999) and a cover of [[Don McLean]]'s \"[[American Pie (song)#Madonna version|American Pie]]\" (2000).<ref name=\"grammy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/GRAMMY_Awards/Winners/Results.aspx?title=&winner=Madonna&year=0&genreID=0&hp=1|title=Grammy Award Winners \u2013 Madonna|publisher=[[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]]|accessdate=December 31, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090111041645/http://www.grammy.com/GRAMMY_Awards/Winners/Results.aspx?title=&winner=Madonna&year=0&genreID=0&hp=1|archivedate=January 11, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Taylor|first=Chuck|date=February 12, 2000|title=Spotlight: Madonna \"American Pie\"|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4Q0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA22|volume=112|issue=7|page=22|issn=0006-2510|accessdate=December 31, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/madonna/2653|title=NME Track Reviews \u2013 American Pie|work=[[NME]]|date=February 26, 2000|accessdate=December 31, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304092920/http://www.nme.com/reviews/madonna/2653|archivedate=March 4, 2016}}</ref>  The singer also became pregnant with her son Rocco, from her relationship with director [[Guy Ritchie]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hoffman|first1=Bill|title=Pregnancy is '2nd' nature for Madonna|url=https://nypost.com/2000/03/21/pregnancy-is-2nd-nature-for-madonna/|work=[[New York Post]]|accessdate=November 2, 2018|date=March 21, 2000}}</ref>  Wanting to distract herself from the media frenzy, Madonna concentrated on the development of her eighth studio album, ''[[Music (Madonna album)|Music]]''.<ref name=\"obr1\">{{harvnb|O'Brien|2008|p=338}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2000, it was announced that French musician [[Mirwais Ahmadza\u00ef]] was creating a melding of dance and pop songs with a disco feel for the album.<ref>{{cite news|title=Madonna Taps French Musician Mirwais To Co-Produce Upcoming Album|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/821128/madonna-taps-french-musician-mirwais-to-co-produce-upcoming-album/|accessdate=July 12, 2014|publisher=MTV News|date=April 18, 2000|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715033528/http://www.mtv.com/news/821128/madonna-taps-french-musician-mirwais-to-co-produce-upcoming-album/|archivedate=July 15, 2014}}</ref> Later, it was also announced that she enlisted [[Guy Sigsworth]] to work with her on the album.<ref name=\"billaugust\">{{cite journal|last=Walter|first=Barry|date=August 5, 2000|title=Madonna Offers Upbeat 'Music' on Maverick|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mBAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA1|journal=Billboard|issn=0006-2510|accessdate=May 14, 2012|issue=32|volume=112|page=98}}</ref> The singer had followed Sigsworth's work, admired his love of understated technology in music, and contacted him for adding an [[ambient music|ambient]] feel to her record. Madonna played him the rough demo tracks developed for ''Music'', including the songs created with Ahmadza\u00ef.<ref name=\"lucy\"/> The idea for \"What It Feels Like for a Girl\" came to Madonna when she was halfway through her pregnancy and was trying to keep the media from finding out.<ref name=Interview/> Sigsworth sent her a demo backing track containing a [[Sampling (music)|sample]] from the 1993 British film [[The Cement Garden (film)|''The Cement Garden'']], directed by [[Andrew Birkin]], in which the voice of actress [[Charlotte Gainsbourg]] speaks softly, \"Girls can wear jeans and cut their hair short, wear shirts and boots. 'Cause it's OK to be a boy. But for a boy to look like a girl is degrading. 'Cause ''you'' think that ''being'' a girl is degrading. But secretly you'd love to know what it's like... Wouldn't you? What it feels like for a girl\".<ref name=\"lucy\">{{harvnb|O'Brien|2008|pp=343\u2013346}}</ref><ref name=Fouz>{{harvnb|Fouz-Hern\u00e1ndez|Jarman-Ivens|2004|p=30}}</ref>\n\nMadonna listened to the phrase uttered by Gainsbourg and started writing the song and the melody, resulting in \"What It Feels Like for a Girl\", a track described by her as a complaint about the politics of sexes.<ref name=\"lucy\"/> She was going through some emotional turmoil due to living on a different continent than her husband Guy Ritchie.<ref name=Interview/> Due to her pregnancy she decided to move to England to be close to him. \"Being the girl, I made the first compromise. It's that extra thing that [women] have. I don't think that we're better than men, but I believe there's an extra accommodating chromosome\", she told ''[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]''{{'}}s [[Ingrid Sischy]].<ref name=Interview/> Madonna reflected on how her generation of women had been encouraged to be independent, be educated and take over any opportunity life bestowed upon them. But she had realized that being a smart and accomplished woman can come across as threat to men, thereby making them a casualty. Madonna questioned, \"Why didn't somebody tell me? Why didn't somebody warn me?' And that's also what that song is about\u2014swallowing that bitter pill... It was a combination of that, and also just feeling incredibly vulnerable that inspired the song.\"<ref name=Fouz/>\n\n==Recording and composition==\n[[File:SSL9000.jpg|thumb|left|A [[Solid State Logic|SSL 9000 J]] console was used for recording the song at [[Sarm West Studios]]|alt=A recording console inside a studio.]]\nSigsworth demo track was the second of two sketches presented to Madonna, and she chose the one with the sample from ''The Cement Garden''. It was almost finished but was still kept unpolished so that the singer could continue writing on top of it.<ref name=\"sos\"/> He recorded the track at [[Sarm West Studios]] rather than his own studio since he did not want to \"fuck up\" working with Madonna.<ref name=\"lucy\"/> The song was finished quickly and within four days they were able to create the final version. From the first day onward Madonna and Sigsworth decided to keep all the musical noises from the demo. So the producer had to find a way to reposition Madonna's vocals around the segments, utilizing [[Pro Tools]] on a [[Solid State Logic|SSL 9000 J]] console.<ref name=\"sos\">{{cite journal|title=Guy Sigsworth: Music After MIDI|url=http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/mar01/articles/guy.asp|accessdate=July 20, 2014|journal=[[Sound on Sound]]|last=Inglis|first=Sam|date=March 2001|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924130251/http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/mar01/articles/guy.asp|archivedate=September 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"credits\"/> Madonna insisted Sigsworth to give her a rough approximate sound, rather than work on the music for two-three hours. That way they would know if it can be kept or rejected and save time on production. During recording, Sigsworth noticed that the [[verse (popular music)|verses]] were out of sync with the music and wanted to add extra [[bar (music)|bar]] which would help them be coherent. However Madonna dismissed it, and he had to cut up the individual music to put it in his computer for accompanying her vocals. Sigsworth thought it made the song sound more \"fluid and magical\" and commended Madonna for not taking the cop-out solution.<ref name=\"lucy\"/>\n\n\"What It Feels Like for a Girl\" is an [[Electronic dance music|electronic]] [[synth-pop]] semi-ballad.<ref name=\"billreview\" /><ref name=\"allmusic2\">{{cite web|last=Promis|first=Jose F.|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/what-it-feels-like-for-a-girl-mw0000005161|title=Music \u2013 What It Feels Like for a Girl|website=[[AllMusic]]|date=April 10, 2001|accessdate=April 26, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180521132040/https://www.allmusic.com/album/what-it-feels-like-for-a-girl-mw0000005161|archivedate=May 21, 2018}}</ref> Madonna and Sigsworth were listed as songwriters and producers on the track with additional production by [[Spike Stent|Mark \"Spike\" Stent]].<ref name=liner>{{cite AV media notes|others=Madonna|title=[[Music (Madonna album)|Music]]|year=2000|type=Liner notes|publisher=[[Maverick Records]]|id=93624-78652-8}}</ref> American guitarist [[David Torn]] was credited as an additional songwriter after Madonna found out Sigsworth had sampled from Torn's 1987 album, ''[[Cloud About Mercury]]''.<ref>{{cite news|year=2012|last1=Prasad|first1=Anil|title=David Torn \u2013 Intersecting ambitions|url=http://www.innerviews.org/inner/torn4.html|accessdate=April 26, 2018|work=Innerviews|authorlink=Anil Prasad|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411174952/http://www.innerviews.org/inner/torn4.html|archivedate=April 11, 2018}}</ref> Stent recorded \"What It Feels Like for a Girl\" using a [[Digital Audio Stationary Head|Sony 3348 HR]] and a BASF 931 tape. He [[audio mixing (recorded music)|mixed]] it at London's [[Olympic Studios]] using SSL G Series [[Quantegy]] magnetic tapes. Tim Young [[audio mastering|mastered]] the track at [[Metropolis Group|Metropolis Studio]] at Westminster, London.<ref name=\"credits\">{{cite web|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/00s/2001/BB-2001-06-09.pdf|title=Pro Audio: Production Credits Billboard's No. 1 Singles|date=June 2, 2001|accessdate=May 18, 2018|work=Billboard|page=60}}</ref>\n\n{{Listen\n | filename    = Madonna - what it feels like for a girl.ogg\n | title       = 'What It Feels Like for a Girl'\n | description = A sample of \"What It Feels Like For a Girl\", a midtempo track with lyrics inviting listeners to imagine themselves as girls.<ref name=Fouz/> The sample illustrates the drum sounds and the rhythm section supported by string pads. It also illustrates when the drums are pulled out just before the chorus starts.\n}}\nAccording to the sheet music published by Musicnotes.com, the song is set in [[Time signature|common time]], with a [[tempo]] of 104 [[beats per minute]]s. It's set in the [[key (music)|key]] of [[E-flat major|E{{flat}} major]], with Madonna's vocals spanning from the lower octave of [[G (musical note)|G<sub>3</sub>]] to the higher note of [[B-flat (musical note)|B{{flat}}<sub>4</sub>]]. The song has a sequence of D{{flat}}<sub>maj9</sub>\u2013E{{flat}}\u2013E{{flat}}/F\u2013A{{flat}} during the verses and F<sub>9sus4</sub>\u2013A{{flat}}\u2013D{{flat}}<sub>maj9</sub>\u2013E{{flat}} during the chorus as its [[chord progression]].<ref name=\"musicnotes1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0060115|title=Madonna Ciccone: What It Feels Like for a Girl|publisher=Musicnotes.com. [[Alfred Publishing]]|accessdate=April 23, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412145237/https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0060115|archivedate=April 12, 2018}}</ref> The track begins with Gainsbourg's monologue which is followed by drum sounds, a rhythm section supported by string pads, and the chord sequence which highlights the melody.<ref name=\"rik\">{{harvnb|Rooksby|2004|p=59}}</ref> Madonna sings over a synth line the first verse, \"Silky smooth lips as sweet as candy, baby/Tight blue jeans, skin that shows in patches\" in a mellow and feminine tone, which is driven by a \"cool beat\" and filtered [[Bass guitar|bass]] licks.<ref name=Fouz/><ref name=\"BestProductions\" /> The ambient production has a number of sounds floating in-and-out of the track, long [[echo]]s and vocals being pulled back.<ref name=\"rik\"/>\n\nAs the pre-chorus ends, the drums are pulled out and added immediately the [[chorus (song)|chorus]] starts, washed over by tidal keys and pads, and Madonna asking the question, \"Do you know what it feels like for a girl?\".<ref name=\"rik\"/><ref name=\"BestProductions\" /> Phil Dellio from ''[[The Village Voice]]'' noticed the presence of \"gossamer-like\" synthesizer in the background, while author Rikky Rooksby highlighted the [[Equalization (audio)|equalized]] bass guitar in the center of the production.<ref name=\"rik\"/><ref name=\"TheVillageVoice\">{{cite web|last1=Dellio|first1=Phill|title=Act of Contrition|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2000/09/19/act-of-contrition/2/|work=[[The Village Voice]]|accessdate=April 26, 2018|date=September 19, 2000}}</ref> Another characteristic Sigsworth feature is the sound of a CD player \"skipping\" during the song.<ref name=\"sos\"/> A Spanish version of the track, titled \"Lo Que Siente la Mujer\" (English: ''What a Woman Feels''), was translated by Alberto Ferreras and included as the [[A-side and B-side|B-side]] of the US CD maxi single release, as well as on the bonus disc of the 2001 Special Tour edition of ''Music'' and as a bonus track on the Mexican and Latin American editions.<ref name=\"US Maxi Single\">{{cite AV media notes|title=What It Feels Like for a Girl|others=Madonna|year=2001|type=JP CD single liner notes|publisher=Maverick Records|id=WPCR-10906}}</ref><ref name=\"touralbum\">{{cite AV media notes|others=Madonna|title=Music: Special Tour edition|year=2001|type=Liner notes|publisher=Maverick Records|id=9362481352}}</ref><ref name=\"mexico\">{{cite AV media notes|others=Madonna|title=Music|year=2001|type=Liner notes|publisher=Maverick Records|id=9362-48135-2}}</ref> Stan Hawkins, author of ''Critical Musicological Reflections'', felt that by switching \"girl\" to \"woman\" in the Spanish version, Madonna had \"upgraded\" its nature.<ref>{{harvnb|Hawkins|2012|p=35}}</ref> Lyrically, \"What It Feels Like for a Girl\" condemns male chauvinism by addressing hurtful myths about female inferiority and female role-playing in society, with the singer inviting men to imagine themselves as girls.<ref name=Fouz/>\n\n==Release and remixes==\n[[File:Above & Beyond 2011.jpg|thumb|left| English group [[Above & Beyond (group)|Above & Beyond]] (pictured in 2011) created one of the official remixes of the song|alt=Three men in black suit standing, with the middle one bending down and laughing to his right.]]\n\"What It Feels Like for a Girl\" was initially planned to be the album's second single, but \"[[Don't Tell Me (Madonna song)|Don't Tell Me]]\" was chosen instead.<ref name=\"billaugust\"/> The song was eventually released as the album's third single on April 17, 2001.<ref name=madonna.com>{{cite web|title=Discography > What It Feels Like For a Girl|url=http://www.madonna.com/discography/index/album/albumId/65/|publisher=Madonna.com|accessdate=July 21, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102070114/http://www.madonna.com/discography/index/album/albumId/65/|archivedate=January 2, 2010}}</ref> Upon release, several [[remix]]es were commissioned, created by [[Above & Beyond (group)|Above & Beyond]], [[Victor Calderone]], [[Richard Vission|Richard \"Humpty\" Vission]], [[Paul Oakenfold]] and [[Tracy Young]].<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=What It Feels Like for a Girl|others=Madonna|year=2000|type=US CD Maxi single liner notes|publisher=Maverick Records|id=9 42372-0}}</ref> The \"Velvet Masta Mix\", created by Richard Vission, gave the song a bass-heavy intro and a funkier groove.<ref name=\"allmusic2\" /> Vission recalled that Madonna had turned down his first mix and asked him to redo it again.<ref name=Arena>{{harvnb|Arena|2017|p=33}}</ref> Calderone's \"Dark Side Mix\" was more mellow, relying more on [[Percussion instrument|percussions]] while Tracy Young's mix included stringed [[harp]] instrumentation. AllMusic's Jose F. Promis praised in particular the Oakenfold version for \"transforming the song into a massive, deep arena club stomper\".<ref name=\"allmusic2\" /> The Above & Beyond remix, which was used for the music video, features \"hard and rhythmic\" pumping beats and removed Madonna's verses, leaving only the chorus and repeating the Charlotte Gainsbourg sample several times in the middle.<ref name=\"Fouz\" />\n\nProduction duo [[Thunderpuss]] was hired to do an official remix of \"What It Feels Like for a Girl\". However, when they were almost finished, an unofficial remix, credited as \"The Thunderpuss Mix\", [[Internet leak|leaked]] on the internet. During an interview with [[About.com]], [[Barry Harris (Canadian musician)|Barry Harris]] from the group recalled that they had been working on the remix and were waiting for it to be approved when they received a call from Warner Bros. Records, informing them that the remix was circulating in the internet. Both [[Chris Cox (DJ)|Chris Cox]] and Harris tried to find out the issue and concluded that someone had retitled the original with their group's name and released it. Thunderpuss tried to convince the record label executives but failed and the remix was canceled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dancemusic.about.com/cs/interviews/a/BarryHarrisInt2_3.htm|last=Slomowicz|first=Ron|title=Barry Harris interview|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050917125545/http://dancemusic.about.com/cs/interviews/a/BarryHarrisInt2_3.htm|publisher=[[About.com]]|accessdate=April 26, 2018|archivedate=September 17, 2005}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Critical reception==\n[[File:Lucy O'Brien 02.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Lucy O'Brien]] (pictured in 2012) praised the track in her book ''[[Madonna: Like an Icon]]''|alt=Lucy O'Brien looking to the front.]]\nUpon release, the song received general acclaim from [[Music journalism|music critics]]. Rikky Rooksby wrote in his book, ''The Complete Guide to the Music of Madonna'' (2004), that \"What It Feels Like for a Girl\" was the best track on ''Music''.<ref name=\"rik\"/> Author [[Lucy O'Brien]] described the song as having a \"beautifully executed sense of anger\" in her 2007 biography, ''[[Madonna: Like an Icon]]''. Likening it to Madonna's 1989 single \"[[Express Yourself (Madonna song)|Express Yourself]]\", O'Brien called it a \"femme-pop\" song.<ref name=\"lucy\"/> [[AllMusic]]'s [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] picked it as one of the album's highlights, calling it a \"terrific midtempo cut\".<ref name=\"allmusic1\">{{cite web|last=Thomas Erlewine|first=Stephen|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/music-r497963/review|title=Music&nbsp;\u2013 Madonna|website=AllMusic|date=September 19, 2000|accessdate=April 8, 2018|authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120123144219/http://www.allmusic.com/album/music-r497963/review|archivedate=January 23, 2012}}</ref> ''[[Slant (magazine)|Slant]]''{{'}}s Sal Cinquemani felt that \"Madonna has revealed more of herself than ever [in ''Music'']. No longer shrouded with pedantic spirituality, she has become even more human [...] revealing her soul on 'What It Feels Like For A Girl'\".<ref name=\"Slant\">{{cite web|last1=Cinquemani|first1=Sal|title=Madonna: Music|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/madonna-music|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|accessdate=April 8, 2018|date=August 20, 2001|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180503180855/https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/madonna-music|archivedate=May 3, 2018}}</ref> However, on his review of ''GHV2'', Cinquemani felt the track was \"largely lost amid the conventional sonics of ''Music''{{'}}s final single\" and called it that compilation's least dynamic offering, giving a C\u2013 rating.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cinquemani|first1=Sal|title=Madonna: GHV2 review|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/madonna-ghv2|work=Slant Magazine|accessdate=April 8, 2018|date=November 8, 2001|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131003130432/http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/madonna-ghv2|archivedate=October 3, 2013}}</ref> Eric Henderson, from the same magazine, wrote that \"occasionally, and only occasionally, Madonna\u2019s reach exceeds her grasp. \u201cWhat It Feels Like for a Girl\u201d is one of those cases. Its intentions feel more fully fleshed out in the controversial music video than they do in the song itself\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Henderson |first=Eric |title=The Beat Goes On: Every Madonna Single Ranked |url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/the-beat-goes-on-every-madonna-single-ranked/2/ |work=Slant Magazine |accessdate=14 May 2019 |date=1 August 2018}}</ref> \n\nNathan Smith from ''[[Houston Press]]'' opined it was \"one of the realest and most mature vocal performances of her career as she gently explores the double standard faced by ambitious women\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Smith |first1=Nathan |title=Madonna's Top 10 Tracks of the 21st Century |url=https://www.houstonpress.com/music/madonnas-top-10-tracks-of-the-21st-century-8062468 |website=[[Houston Press]] |accessdate=1 May 2019 |date=January 11, 2016}}</ref> From ''[[Gay Star News]]'', Joe Morgan called it a \"clear reminder that Madonna can write some incredible lyrics\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Morgan |first1=Joe |title=The Definitive Ranking of Madonna's Top 60 Singles |url=https://www.gaystarnews.com/article/the-definitive-ranking-of-madonnas-top-60-singles/#gs.bxxxb8 |work=[[Gay Star News]] |accessdate=14 May 2019 |date=August 9, 2018}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', journalist [[David Browne (journalist)|David Browne]] relegated the track as \"an older, wiser '[[Into the Groove]]'\", highlighting its \"softly padding beat and genuinely empathetic lyrics\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Browne|first1=David|title=Madonna: Music|url=https://ew.com/article/2000/09/18/music-2/|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=April 8, 2018|date=September 18, 2000|authorlink=David Browne (journalist)|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180521132040/http://ew.com/article/2000/09/18/music-2/|archivedate=May 21, 2018}}</ref> ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' magazine{{'}}s Danny Eccleston picked it as a standout track, claiming it had \"the vaguest melodic echo of [[Basement Jaxx]]'s terrific '[[Red Alert (song)|On & On]]'\".<ref name=q>{{cite news|last1=Eccleston|first1=Dany|year=2000|title=Reviews&nbsp;\u2013 Madonna: Music|url=http://www.qonline.co.uk/reviews/server.asp?id=18961|work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|accessdate=April 13, 2018|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001205203200/http://www.qonline.co.uk/reviews/server.asp?id=18961|archivedate=December 5, 2000}}</ref> Cynthia Funchs of ''[[PopMatters]]'' picked the song as her favorite on the album, calling it \"outstanding\" with \"sweet, enchanted beats\".<ref name=popmatters>{{cite news|last=Fuchs|first=Cynthia|title=Madonna: Music|url=https://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/madonna-music|accessdate=April 13, 2018|work=[[PopMatters]]|date=September 19, 2000|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524083421/http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/madonna-music/|archivedate=May 24, 2013}}</ref> Eamon Sweeney of ''[[Hot Press]]'', found it similar, in tone and texture, to [[Natalie Imbruglia]]'s 1998 single \"[[Smoke (Natalie Imbruglia song)|Smoke]]\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sweeney|first1=Eamon|title=Music reviews \u2013 singles: What It Feels Like For A Girl|url=http://www.hotpress.com/Madonna/music/reviews/singles/What-It-Feels-Like-For-A-Girl/524172.html|work=[[Hot Press]]|accessdate=April 26, 2018|date=April 25, 2001|url-access=subscription |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171021080249/http://www.hotpress.com/Madonna/music/reviews/singles/What-It-Feels-Like-For-A-Girl/524172.html|archivedate=October 21, 2017}}</ref> [[Jon Pareles]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' called it \"Madonna's quasi-feminist statement\".<ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{cite web|last1=Pareles|first1=Jon|title=Pop Review; Madonna and the Wiles of Willfulness|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/07/26/nyregion/pop-review-madonna-and-the-wiles-of-willfulness.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=April 26, 2018|date=July 26, 2001|authorlink=Jon Pareles|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170806024504/http://www.nytimes.com/2001/07/26/nyregion/pop-review-madonna-and-the-wiles-of-willfulness.html|archivedate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s Barry Walters called it \"as musically gentle as it is lyrically barbed\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Walter|first1=Barry|title=Madonna: Music|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/music-20001012|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=April 8, 2018|date=October 12, 2000|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213082941/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/music-20001012|archivedate=December 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nGarry Mulholland of ''[[The Guardian]]'', praised its \"melancholy atmosphere and ambiguous air\".<ref name=\"TheGuardian\">{{cite web|last1=Mulholland|first1=Garry|title=Garry Mulholland wants to like Madonna's Music. Trouble is, it's unbearably naff|url=https://www.theguardian.com/friday_review/story/0,3605,368337,00.html|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=April 13, 2018|date=September 15, 2000}}</ref> Also from ''The Guardian'', Maddy Costa thought that the track was \"exquisite\", adding \"on 'What It Feels Like for a Girl' you feel is the Madonna of old, talking about being a pop bitch and making you tingle even with its hackneyed lyrics\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Costa|first1=Maddy|title=Madonna's saucy gig in Brixton|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2000/nov/30/artsfeatures.madonna|work=The Guardian|accessdate=April 13, 2018|date=November 30, 2000|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180521132040/https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2000/nov/30/artsfeatures.madonna|archivedate=May 21, 2018}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', Larry Flick hailed it \"a hook-laden midtempo jam [...] that should give the [[Britney Spears|Britney]]/[[Christina Aguilera|Christina]] generation of teenage female listeners a little food for thought\", highlighting its \"motherly, nurturing perspective\".<ref name=\"music\">{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mBAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA98|title=Exclusive: Madonna on Music|last=Flick|first=Larry|date=August 5, 2000|accessdate=April 13, 2018|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|issn=0006-2510|page=98|volume=112|issue=32}}</ref> Also from ''Billboard'', Chuck Taylor named it \"one of the more substantive&nbsp;\u2013 and mature&nbsp;\u2013 musical ventures of [Madonna's] career\", while panning its remix version for \"reduc[ing] the song to a mindless trickle of beats without any hints of the verses\".<ref name=billreview>{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=Chuck|title=Reviews & Previews: Singles|journal=Billboard|date=April 7, 2001|volume=113|issue=14|page=20|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uBMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA20|issn=0006-2510|accessdate=April 13, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180521132045/https://books.google.com/books?id=uBMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA20|archivedate=May 21, 2018}}</ref> Alex Pappademas from ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'', pointed out that the song \"flaunts the sexiest synth shimmer this side of [Aguilera's] '[[Genie in a Bottle]]'\".<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pappademas|first1=Alex|title=Reviews: Madonna \u2013 Music|journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|date=October 2000|volume=16|issue=10|page=173|url=https://books.google.es/books?id=HTMuhxamaFEC&pg=PA173|accessdate=April 26, 2018|issn=0886-3032}}</ref> ''[[The Village Voice]]''{{'}}s Phil Dellio found the song to be \"the perfect answer record to [the novel] ''[[The Virgin Suicides]]'' (where boys indeed stand on the side of the street looking uncomprehendingly towards girls)\".<ref name=\"TheVillageVoice\" /> On a more critical note, [[Medium (website)|Medium]]'s Richard LaBeau opined that \"with better production it could have been a true classic\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=LeBeau |first1=Richard |title=Ranking All 57 of Madonna\u2019s Billboard Hits in Honor of Her 60th(!) Birthday |url=https://medium.com/rants-and-raves/ranking-all-57-of-madonnas-billboard-hits-in-honor-of-her-60th-birthday-b4f5e2d10fcd |publisher=[[Medium (website)|Medium]] |accessdate=2 June 2019 |date=August 16, 2018}}</ref> Online magazine ''[[Queerty]]'' felt the Spanish version, \"Lo Que Siente la Mujer\", was \"an effort, we assume, to prove she ''can'' speak Spanish, damn it! Or at least memorize enough words to ''sound'' like she speaks Spanish\".<ref>{{cite web |title=You can dance: Madonna\u2019s Spanish-language songs ranked |url=https://www.queerty.com/madonnas-spanish-language-songs-ranked-20190421 |website=[[Queerty]] |accessdate=11 July 2019 |date=21 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\nWhile listing \"The 100 Greatest Madonna Songs\", Louis Virtel from ''[[AfterEllen.com and TheBacklot.com|The Backlot]]'' ranked \"What It Feels Like for a Girl\" at number 45, saying that \"its tenderness and power resonated like no Madonna ballad since '[[Take a Bow (Madonna song)|Take a Bow]]'\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Virtel|first1=Louis|title=The 100 Greatest Madonna Songs|url=http://www.newnownext.com/the-100-greatest-madonna-songs/02/2012/|publisher=[[AfterEllen.com and TheBacklot.com|TheBacklot.com]]|accessdate=December 30, 2017|date=February 3, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805180215/http://www.newnownext.com/the-100-greatest-madonna-songs/02/2012/|archivedate=August 5, 2017}}</ref> In 2013, Scott Kearnan of [[Boston.com]] included it at number 26 on his list of \"30 Ultimate Madonna Singles\"; he wrote that \"Madonna's covered plenty of ground about how women are treated in the world, but she's rarely this unfiltered\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kearnan|first1=Scott|title=The 30 ultimate Madonna singles|url=http://archive.boston.com/ae/music/30_best_madonna_singles_ultimate_song_list/|work=[[Boston Globe]]|accessdate=April 13, 2018|date=September 9, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729221509/http://archive.boston.com/ae/music/30_best_madonna_singles_ultimate_song_list/|archivedate=July 29, 2017}}</ref> The same year, Edward Cheung from ''PopMatters'' ranked it as the sixth best production by Guy Sigsworth, writing that \"an excellently placed spoken word sample (delivered by Charlotte Gainsbourg) and a keening synth line immediately set the tone for Madge's track as fashionably lonely\".<ref name=BestProductions>{{cite web|last1=Cheung|first1=Edward|title=The 10 Best Productions by... Guy Sigsworth|url=https://www.popmatters.com/170907-10-best-productions-by-guy-sigsworth-2495760767.html|work=PopMatters|accessdate=April 26, 2018|date=May 1, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412213228/https://www.popmatters.com/170907-10-best-productions-by-guy-sigsworth-2495760767.html|archivedate=April 12, 2018}}</ref>  Matthew Jacob's from ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' ranked the track at number 51 on his list \"The Definitive Ranking of Madonna Singles\", pointing out its \"meaningful lyrical accomplishment\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jacobs|first1=Matthew|title=The Definitive Ranking Of Madonna Singles|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/04/22/the-definitive-ranking-of-madonna-singles_n_5078934.html|work=[[HuffPost]]|accessdate=December 30, 2017|date=March 10, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160327133855/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/04/22/the-definitive-ranking-of-madonna-singles_n_5078934.html|archivedate=March 27, 2016}}</ref> While ranking Madonna's singles in honor of her 60th birthday, in August 2018, [[Jude Rogers]] from ''The Guardian'' placed the track at number 37 and wrote that \"it sounds like a [[Saint Etienne (band)|Saint Etienne]] song accidentally covered by a superstar\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rogers|first1=Jude| authorlink = Jude Rogers |title=Every one of Madonna's 78 singles \u2013 ranked!|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/aug/16/every-one-of-madonnas-78-singles-ranked|work=The Guardian|accessdate=August 26, 2018|date=August 16, 2018}}</ref> ''Entertainment Weekly''{{'}}s Chuck Arnold called it \"one of Madonna\u2019s artistic peaks\" and her \"most underappreciated\" release; he listed it as her 14th best single.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Arnold|first1=Chuck|title=Madonna's 60 best singles, ranked|url=https://ew.com/music/2018/08/15/madonnas-60-best-singles-ranked/|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=September 28, 2018|date=August 15, 2018}}</ref> On 2019, Samuel R. Murrian from ''[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]'' ranked it at number 16 on his list of the singer's 100 greatest songs: \"Lyrically barbed but sonically soft, one of Madonna\u2019s most radical tracks explores the brutality of being a woman in a man\u2019s world. [...] Though it was recorded nearly two decades before the [[Me Too movement|#MeToo]] movement, this track feels like an anthem for it. Madonna was, and is, ahead of her time\u201d.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Murrian |first1=Samuel R. |title=We Ranked the 100 Best Madonna Songs of All Time |url=https://parade.com/897929/samuelmurrian/best-madonna-songs-ranked/ |work=[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]] |accessdate=17 August 2019 |date=August 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"What It Feels Like for a Girl\" debuted at number 73 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart of May 5, 2001, and moved to number 46 the following week, becoming in the biggest leap of that week.<ref name=billdebut>{{cite journal|title=The Billboard Hot 100|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=May 12, 2001|volume=113|issue=19|pages=142\u2013143|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FikEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA104|accessdate=July 21, 2014|issn=0006-2510|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180521132040/https://books.google.com/books?id=FikEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA104|archivedate=May 21, 2018}}</ref> The release of the DVD single, CD maxi and 12-inch vinyl prompted the song to debut at number 15 on the [[Hot 100 Singles Sales]] chart with 6,600 copies (majority being from the DVD single).<ref name=\"dvdsingle\"/> The song peaked at number 23 on the issue dated May 19, 2001, becoming that week's greatest gainer in sales.<ref name=\"bb100\"/> The same week, it also reached the top of the [[Dance Club Songs]] chart.<ref name=bbdance/> At the year-end ranking for 2001, the song placed at number 24 on Dance Club Songs.<ref name=\"bbyear\"/> According to Madonna's official website since only a [[maxi single]] was released commercially, it hindered the chart placement on ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name=madonna.com/> In Canada, the song debuted at number 14 on the [[Canadian Singles Chart]], and reached a peak of number two after two weeks later.<ref name=\"candebut\">{{cite web|title=Hits of the World: Canada|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/00s/2001/BB-2001-05-12.pdf|work=Billboard|page=48|date=May 12, 2001|accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"can\"/>\n\nIn Australia, \"What It Feels Like for a Girl\" debuted and peaked at number six on the [[ARIA Charts]], on May 6, 2001, and was present in the top-fifty for nine weeks, and was ranked number 84 on the year-end placements.<ref name=\"aus\"/><ref name=\"ausyear\"/> The track also reached the top of the Australian dance charts.<ref name=\"ausdance\"/> It was certified Gold by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA) for shipment of 35,000 copies of the single.<ref name=\"aria\"/> The song debuted at number 50 on the [[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand|New Zealand Singles Chart]], and reached a peak of number 15 after six weeks.<ref name=nz/>\n\nIn the United Kingdom, \"What It Feels Like for a Girl\" managed to become the third song from ''Music'' to peak inside the top-ten, reaching number seven on April 28, 2001.<ref name=\"uk\"/> According to the [[Official Charts Company]], it has sold 86,771 copies in the country as of August 2008.<ref name=\"uksales\"/> The song was successful across Europe, reaching the top-ten of the charts in Denmark, Finland, Italy, Netherlands and Spain.<ref name=\"dk\"/><ref name=\"spa\"/> However, in some countries, \"What It Feels Like for a Girl\" failed to reach the top-twenty. In Austria and Sweden, the song reached numbers 26 and 22, respectively, becoming her lowest-charting single since \"[[Nothing Really Matters]]\" (1999) in both countries.<ref name=\"aut\"/><ref name=\"swe\"/> In France, the song debuted and peaked at number 40 on the [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|French Singles Chart]], and descended rapidly.<ref name=\"fra\"/> The track managed to reach the top-ten of the [[European Hot 100 Singles]] chart, reaching number eight on May 5, 2001.<ref name=\"euro\"/> It was also the most played song on European radios, holding the top position for five weeks.<ref name=euroyearend/>\n\n==Music video==\n===Background and synopsis===\n[[File:GuyRitchiebyKathyHutchins.jpg|thumb|upright|The music video was directed by Madonna's then-husband [[Guy Ritchie]] (pictured in 2017)|alt=Guy Ritchie in a blue coat looking to the right.]]\nIn February 2001, English filmmaker [[Guy Ritchie]], Madonna's then husband, said that they were planning to work together on her new music video; \"creatively, we like the same sort of things, so it just makes sense\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.madonna.com/news/title/guy-ritchie-to-direct-madonna-couple-set-to-make-video|title=Guy Ritchie to direct Madonna, Couple set to make video|date=February 13, 2001|accessdate=May 20, 2018|publisher=Madonna.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015014904/http://www.madonna.com/news/title/guy-ritchie-to-direct-madonna-couple-set-to-make-video|archivedate=October 15, 2017}}</ref> One month later, Madonna revealed to Ingrid Sischy that the video would be for \"What It Feels Like for a Girl\", which she found \"ironic because [Ritchie]'s such a macho man, and his movies are so testosterone-driven, but I asked him a long time ago what song on the album he responded to the most, and that's the one\".<ref name=Interview>{{cite journal|title=Madonna Exclusive! The Ultimate Interview with Ingrid Sischy|date=March 2001|last=Sischy|first=Ingrid|authorlink=Ingrid Sischy|journal=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> Filming took place in Los Angeles, including on the [[Olympic Boulevard (Los Angeles)|Olympic Boulevard]]. According to Madonna she portrayed a \"[[nihilism|nihilistic]] pissed-off chick\" in the clip, doing things that girls are generally recommended against. The video did not feature the original version of the song but the Above & Beyond remix since the singer \"wanted a matching visual to it and an edgy dance mix\".<ref name=Showsoff>{{cite web|title=Madonna Shows Off New Video|url=http://www.madonna.com/news/title/madonna-shows-off-new-video|publisher=Madonna.com|accessdate=March 22, 2018|date=March 20, 2001}}</ref>\n\nThe clip starts with the singer in a motel room getting ready to go out, her hair is straight, chin length and parted down the middle.<ref name=\"NicholasEntertainment\" /> She then [[Hot-wiring|hot-wire]]s a yellow 1978 [[Chevrolet Camaro]] from the parking lot, with the license plates reading \"Pussy\" and \"Cat\" on the front and back, before driving to the \"Ol Kuntz Guest Home\" to pick up a semi-[[catatonic]] elderly woman.<ref name=\"BianculliNY\" /> At a traffic light, they stop next to a car with three young men who make lewd gestures at them, which prompts Madonna to spin her car around and [[Side collision|collide]] them.<ref name=\"NewsOK\" /> She parks at an [[Automated teller machine|ATM]], [[taser]]s a man and steals his money, and later gives it to a waitress at a burger place.<ref name=\"BianculliNY\" /><ref name=\"SFChronicle\" /> The singer continues to drive in front of a [[police car]] and squirts water on the face of two policemen from a fake pistol before driving backwards into their car.<ref name=\"BianculliNY\" /> She then mows down a pack of [[street hockey]] players before stealing a red [[muscle car]] from a gas station where an [[Filling station attendant|attendant]] fills its tank, spilling gasoline all over the pavement. Madonna then throws a lighter out of the window causing an explosion, all while still accompanied by the old woman.<ref name=\"BianculliNY\" /> The final shot depicts her slamming the stolen car head-on into a telephone pole in an apparent act of [[murder\u2013suicide]].<ref name=\"NewsOK\"/>\n\n===Release and banning===\n[[File:Madonna - What It Feels Like for a Girl (music video).jpg|left|thumb|Still from the music video, depicting Madonna aiming a water gun at a cop. Next to her is the elderly woman she picks up from the \"Ol Kuntz Guest Home\".|alt=Refer to caption.]]\nUpon release, the video was criticized for its violent content. Music channels [[MTV]] and [[VH1]] said that it would not be added to their regular US rotation and would air it just once, during a news segment, before being completely [[Censorship in the United States|banned]].<ref name=\"MTVNews\">{{cite web|last1=MTV Staff|title=Madonna's new Video: Too hot for TV!|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1441849/madonnas-new-video-too-hot-for-tv/|publisher=[[MTV News]]|accessdate=April 6, 2018|date=March 19, 2001}}</ref> This was Madonna's third video to be banned by the channel, following \"[[Justify My Love]]\" (1990) and \"[[Erotica (song)|Erotica]]\" (1992).<ref name=\"SFChronicle\" /> \"What It Feels Like for a Girl\" aired on March 20, 2001, at 11:30 pm, following an introduction by MTV News anchor [[Kurt Loder]].<ref name=\"BianculliNY\" /> Liz Rosenberg, Madonna's publicist, released a statement urging the channels \"to make a very strong commitment to playing this video [...] there are many other possibilities that we can explore but our first choice has always been for VH1 and MTV to play [the video], and more than once\".<ref name=\"Farache\"/> In 2002, the video was aired in its entirety on [[MTV2]] as part of a special countdown of the year's most controversial videos.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/onair/controversialvideos/controvids.jhtml|title=The Controversial Videos|publisher=MTV|accessdate=May 1, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020521203844/http://www.mtv.com/onair/controversialvideos/controvids.jhtml|archivedate=May 21, 2002}}</ref>\n\nThree days later, the clip was shown several times on [[Oxygen (TV channel)|Oxygen]] as part of its \"Daily Remix\" music series.<ref>{{cite web|title=Controversial Madonna Video Hits Oxygen|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/80295/controversial-madonna-video-hits-oxygen|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 7, 2018|date=March 22, 2001}}</ref> A spokeswoman for Oxygen said that the decision to air the video multiple times was because \"our demographic is of 18\u201349 year old women [...] older than MTV's\". Other channels such as [[Much (TV channel)|MuchMusic]] followed and aired the video several times throughout the day and night.<ref name=\"BillboardBans\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/00s/2001/BB-2001-04-07.pdf|title=MTV, VH1 ban Madonna's video, but other networks still air it|last=Hay|first=Carla|date=April 7, 2001|accessdate=April 7, 2018|work=Billboard|page=103}}</ref> Norm Schoenfield, US VP of programming for MuchMusic, released a statement saying \"[the video] is no more or less violent than what kids see on TV everyday. We weren't offended by it, and treating it just like any other Madonna video. Just because MTV isn't playing it, doesn't mean we can't\". Schoenfield also criticized the decision of releasing an advisory warning alongside the video because \"it's the artist's responsibility to do that\". Nonetheless, other Canadian networks aired it only after 9 pm accompanied by a warning.<ref name=\"BillboardBans\" /> There were also talks of airing the video on [[HBO]] but it never happened.<ref name=\"Farache\"/><ref name=\"BillboardBans\"/>\n\nFollowing the controversy with MTV, Warner Bros. Records signed a deal with [[America Online|AOL]] to air the video online on its music forums. \"Our job as a record company is to get exposure for the video, So when the label couldn't get Viacom to commit to showing the video, it started talking to other outlets\", explained Rosenberg.<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Hane C.|title=Controversial new Madonna video airs on the Web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2001/TECH/internet/03/23/madonna.video.idg/index.html|publisher=[[CNN]]|accessdate=April 7, 2018|date=March 23, 2001}}</ref> On April 24, 2001, the video was released as a [[DVD single]] with the disc having linear [[Pulse-code modulation|PCM]] sound quality.<ref name=\"NYRock\" /> It debuted on ''Billboard''{{'}}s Top Music Video sales chart at number two with 6,200 copies sold, the highest sum for a DVD single since Madonna's clip for \"Music\", which had sold 4,200 copies in September 2000.<ref name=\"dvdsingle\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/00s/2001/BB-2001-05-12.pdf|title=Hot 100 Spotlight|last=Pietroluongo|first=Silvio|date=May 12, 2001|accessdate=April 7, 2018|work=Billboard|page=143}}</ref><ref name=\"usvideo\"/> The clip was later included on Madonna's 2009 compilation, ''[[Celebration: The Video Collection]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2009/08/26/madonna-celebration-track-list|title=Madonna's 'Celebration' track list revealed: Are the greatest hits all there?|last=Greenblatt|first=Leah|date=August 26, 2009|accessdate=December 30, 2017|work=Entertainment Weekly|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180116135156/http://www.ew.com/article/2009/08/26/madonna-celebration-track-list/|archivedate=January 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Folkard|2002|p=1940}}</ref> Regarding the violent content, Madonna said that her intention was to \"make people ask questions and open dialogues\".<ref name=NYRock>{{cite web|title=Madonna's Controversial 'What It Feels Like for a Girl' DVD Single Set for Release April 24th|url=http://www.nyrock.com/worldbeat/04_2001/042301.asp|publisher=NY Rock|accessdate=April 7, 2018|date=April 12, 2001|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010430143906/http://www.nyrock.com/worldbeat/04_2001/042301.asp|archivedate=April 30, 2001}}</ref> Rosenberg explained to ''[[New York Daily News]]'' that the clip told the story of a woman who had probably been abused, and called it a \"kind of an anti-violence film. I can't imagine anyone would want to duplicate it\". The apparent suicide at the end had references from [[Greek mythology]], according to Ritchie.<ref name=\"Farache\">{{cite web|last1=Farache|first1=Emily|title=MTV bans Madonna Vid|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/41326/mtv-bans-madonna-vid|publisher=[[E!]]|accessdate=April 6, 2018|date=March 19, 2001}}</ref>\n\n===Reception and analysis===\n[[David Bianculli]] from the ''New York Daily News'' felt that \"Madonna has always kept her videos and images at least as fresh as her music. 'What It Feels Like for a Girl', though, is a bad attempt to chase attention by promising controversy\".<ref name=\"BianculliNY\">{{cite web|last1=Bianculli|first1=David|authorlink1=David Bianculli|title=Madonna video shoots a blank|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/entertainment/madonna-video-shoots-blank-article-1.914671|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|location=New York|accessdate=April 5, 2018|date=March 22, 2001}}</ref> Similarly, ''Billboard''{{'}}s Carla Hay concluded that the video did not live up to its hype.<ref name=\"BillboardBans\" /> George Lang from ''[[The Oklahoman]]'', called it as the singer's worst clip and criticized Ritchie's directing abilities; \"he has great visual sense, but his work often is lacking depth. Both his asset and his debit were in ample evidence in [the video]\".<ref name=\"NewsOK\">{{cite web|last1=Lang|first1=George|title=New video from Madonna crashes and burns|url=http://newsok.com/article/2734982|work=[[The Oklahoman]]|accessdate=April 5, 2018|date=March 23, 2001}}</ref> ''Entertainment Weekly''{{'}}s Nicholas Fonseca gave the video a rating of C and opined that \"''[[Thelma and Louise]]'' it ain't. In fact, little girls can probably find more empowerment copying Britney Spears' provocative chair dance from her '[[Stronger (Britney Spears song)|Stronger]]' video\". But he criticized MTV's decision to ban the clip when they aired much more violent videos on the channel.<ref name=\"NicholasEntertainment\">{{cite web|last1=Fonseca|first1=Nicholas|title=What It Feels Like for a Girl|url=https://ew.com/article/2001/03/22/what-it-feels-girl/|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=April 5, 2018|date=March 21, 2001|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819144134/http://ew.com/article/2001/03/22/what-it-feels-girl/|archivedate=August 19, 2017}}</ref> Eden Miller from ''PopMatters'' echoed this sentiment, adding that MTV aired videos such as [[Eminem]]'s \"[[Stan (song)|Stan]]\", in which the main character drives his car off a bridge with his pregnant girlfriend tied up in the trunk, or [[Robbie Williams]]' \"[[Rock DJ]]\", in which the singer strips his skin off in graphic detail. Miller relegated the banning due to Madonna being a woman \"and the idea of a woman taking her aggression out on men is something the network can just not have. That's what is so disturbing. And that really is what it feels like for a girl\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Miller|first1=Eden|title=What it Feels Like for the Material Girl|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050415161837/http://popmatters.com/music/videos/m/madonna-what.html|url=https://popmatters.com/music/videos/m/madonna-what.html|accessdate=April 5, 2018|archivedate=April 15, 2005|date=March 2001|work=[[PopMatters]]|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nWriting for the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'', Neva Chonin accused the video for being a [[Marketing strategy|marketing ploy]] and believed that the singer knew it would result in controversy and drive sales amidst the publicity. Nonetheless, she praised it for being a follow-up to Madonna's aesthetics and changing of her looks from her early career. Chonin realized that by making the violent video, Madonna proved the song's concept further by making a girl behave violently in place of a boy.<ref name=\"SFChronicle\">{{cite web|last1=Chonin|first1=Neva|title=Madonna's No 'Pussy Cat' / MTV bans her latest video, again|url=https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Madonna-s-No-Pussy-Cat-MTV-bans-her-latest-3268215.php|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|accessdate=April 5, 2018|date=March 23, 2001|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728202643/http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Madonna-s-No-Pussy-Cat-MTV-bans-her-latest-3268215.php|archivedate=July 28, 2017}}</ref> Louis Virtel from [[AfterEllen.com and TheBacklot.com|The Backlot]] ranked it as the singer's 12th greatest video, calling it \"the ultimate (read: solely tolerable) Madonna/Guy Ritchie collaboration [...] She's both chilling and totally confident. It\u2019s her most frightening performance in a music video, and when she plows that car into a group of strangers, her stoic response makes for her greatest video moment of the 2000s\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Virtel |first1=Louis |title=Madonna\u2019s 55 Best Videos, In Honor of Her 55th Birthday |url=http://www.newnownext.com/madonnas-55-best-videos-in-honor-of-her-55th-birthday/08/2013/ |publisher=[[AfterEllen.com and TheBacklot.com]] |accessdate=26 April 2019 |date=August 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAuthor [[Andrew Morton (writer)|Andrew Morton]] opined that the video was \"entirely consistent with the themes [Madonna] has been exploring for the last twenty years, namely the relationship between the sexes, the ambiguity of gender, and the unresolved conflict, for women in a patriarchal society of being fully female and sexual while exercising control over their lives\".<ref>{{harvnb|Morton|2002|p=183}}</ref> According to Santiago Fouz-Hern\u00e1ndez and Freya Jarman-Ivens, authors of ''Madonna's Drowned Worlds'', the video represented the female fantasy of behaving like a \"bad boy\" and doing things associated with men. They pointed out the scene in which Madonna winks at three men at a traffic light just before crashing their car, as they felt that on this particular shot she was \"turning the tables of violence back on the men for whom such behavior is considered ''normal'' and putting them on the receiving end of violence, a position usually reserved for women\".<ref name=\"santiago\"/> They noticed that unlike previous Madonna videos which were banned for religious themes or sexuality, MTV found violence as an offence. Even using the remix in the clip changed the song's feminine and bittersweet nature to something faster and harder, adjectives usually reserved for boys. The authors concluded that as always, Madonna inverted the traditional roles and characterization of male and female in the clip.<ref name=\"santiago\">{{harvnb|Fouz-Hern\u00e1ndez|Jarman-Ivens|2004|pp=31\u201333}}</ref>\n\n==Live performances and cover version==\n[[File:LoQueSionteLaMujerDionisio (cropped2).jpg|thumb|Madonna performing \"Lo Que Siente la Mujer\", the Spanish version of \"What It Feels Like for a Girl\",  during the [[Drowned World Tour]] (2001).|alt=Madonna in a black dress atop a sloping structure, with her dancers below.]]\n\"What It Feels Like for a Girl\" was performed on the promotional concerts for ''Music'' in November 2000 at New York City's [[Roseland Ballroom]] and at London's [[Brixton Academy]].<ref name=\"rose\">{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0BAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA37|title=Madonna Celebrates 'Music's' Global Success At Roseland|last=Paoletta|first=Michael|date=November 18, 2000|accessdate=December 30, 2017|work=Billboard|issn=0006-2510|page=37|volume=112|issue=47}}</ref><ref name=\"nyc\">{{cite web|last=Kemp|first=Rob|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431543/madonna-shatters-record-mostviewed-webcast-producer.jhtml|title=Madonna Shatters Record For Most-Viewed Webcast, Producer Says|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=November 29, 2000|accessdate=December 30, 2017}}</ref> On New York, Madonna dedicated the song to singer Britney Spears, while wearing a tank top with Spears' name printed on it.<ref name=\"rose\"/><ref name=\"nyc\"/> For the London performance, she wore a different top imprinted with the names of son Rocco and daughter Lourdes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2000/dec/03/features.review37|title=Madonna gets them in|last=Sawyer|first=Miranda|date=December 3, 2000|accessdate=April 21, 2013|work=The Guardian|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222225856/http://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2000/dec/03/features.review37|archivedate=February 22, 2014}}</ref> Around 3,000&nbsp;fans attended the concert in London, which was [[streaming media|streamed]] over the internet. More than nine million people watched the concert according to Nicky Price, a representative for Microsoft's [[MSN]], the [[webcast]]'s producer.<ref name=\"nyc\"/> It became the most-viewed webcast of all time, beating [[Paul McCartney]]'s performance of \"50s rock and roll classics\" at Liverpool's [[The Cavern Club]] in December 1999, which was viewed by an audience of about three million.<ref name=\"nyc\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1045360.stm|title=Madonna's new hit record|date=November 29, 2000|accessdate=April 21, 2013|work=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222033659/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1045360.stm|archivedate=February 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\nFor the [[Drowned World Tour]] of 2001, a remix of the track was used as a video interlude. Dancers wearing [[anime]] and [[manga]] inspired costumes swung from wires in a Japanese-inspired sequence as the backdrops featured scenes of a naked girl being pursued, trapped and sexually abused. The clips were taken from [[Satoshi Kon]]'s 1997 film ''[[Perfect Blue]]'' interspersed with footage of the [[hentai]] anime ''[[Urotsukid\u014dji]]''.<ref name=\"NYTimes\" /><ref name=\"Steiff\">{{harvnb|Steiff|Tamplin|2010|p=118}}</ref><ref name=\"SlantDrowned\">{{cite web|last1=Cinquemani|first1=Sal|title=Madonna New York, NY&nbsp;\u2013 July 25, 2001|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/features/article/madonna-new-york-ny-july-25-2001|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|accessdate=March 22, 2018|date=July 26, 2001|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171004183503/https://www.slantmagazine.com/features/article/madonna-new-york-ny-july-25-2001|archivedate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> Writing for MTV News, Rob Mancini opined that the interlude video \"upped the [show's] grim factor further\".<ref name=\"RobManciniDWT\">{{cite web|last1=Mancini|first1=Rob|title=Madonna \u2013 all five of her \u2013 invades Philadelphia with 'Drowned World' tour|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1445328/madonna-all-five-of-her-invades-philadelphia-with-tour/|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=March 22, 2018|date=July 23, 2001|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170702123939/http://www.mtv.com/news/1445328/madonna-all-five-of-her-invades-philadelphia-with-tour/|archivedate=July 2, 2017}}</ref> On that same tour, Madonna performed the Spanish version of the song, \"Lo Que Siente La Mujer\", atop a rotating black leather podium, dressed in black trousers and a backless black blouse.<ref name=\"RobManciniDWT\"/> The female dancers were decked in masculine attires while the male dancers wore long wigs and corsets. Academic [[Georges Claude Guilbert]], author of ''Madonna As Postmodern Myth'', praised the performance for its \"gender-bending and further sense of ambiguity\" while Sal Cinquemani from ''Slant Magazine'' found it to be \"anticlimactic\".<ref name=\"SlantDrowned\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Guilbert|2002|p=190}}</ref> The performance on August 26, 2001, at [[The Palace of Auburn Hills]], outside of Madonna's hometown of Detroit was recorded and released in the live [[video album]], ''[[Drowned World Tour 2001]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/78099/madonnas-drowned-comes-to-home-video|last=Trust|first=Gary|work=Billboard|title=Madonna's 'Drowned' Comes To Home Video|date=October 9, 2001|accessdate=March 22, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304120743/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/78099/madonnas-drowned-comes-to-home-video|archivedate=March 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, \"What It Feels Like for a Girl\" was featured in an episode of American television series ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'', called \"[[The Power of Madonna]]\". In the episode it was performed by actors [[Cory Monteith]], [[Kevin McHale (actor)|Kevin McHale]], [[Chris Colfer]], [[Mark Salling]], [[Harry Shum Jr.]] and [[Matthew Morrison]].<ref name=\"glee\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://jezebel.com/5521212/glee--what-it-feels-like-for-a-girl/|title=Glee: What It Feels Like For A Girl|last=Hartmann|first=Margaret|date=April 21, 2010|accessdate=May 20, 2018|website=[[Jezebel (website)|Jezebel]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160608082951/http://jezebel.com/5521212/glee--what-it-feels-like-for-a-girl/|archivedate=June 8, 2016}}</ref> The song was released as [[music download|digital download]] to the [[iTunes Store]], and was also included on the soundtrack EP, ''[[Glee: The Music, The Power of Madonna]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/glee-the-music-the-power-of-madonna/363000290|title=Glee: The Music \u2013 The Power of Madonna|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]|date=April 20, 2010|accessdate=May 1, 2018}}</ref> It charted at number 125 on the UK Singles Chart.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Official Singles Chart for the week ending 8 May 2010|journal=[[ChartsPlus]]|issue=454|pages=1\u20134|date=May 6, 2010|location=Liverpool}}</ref> In his review of the soundtrack, Fraser McAlpine from BBC News felt that \"the decision to get all the boys to sing 'What It Feels Like for a Girl' is inspired, and represents a genuinely powerful musical moment that doesn't need the television show's plot to make it fly\".<ref name=\"glee\">{{cite news|last1=McAlpine|first1=Fraser|title=Glee Cast Glee: The Music, The Power of Madonna Review|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/zfx2/|work=BBC News|accessdate=May 1, 2018|year=2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109110108/http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/zfx2|archivedate=January 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Track listings==\n;EU CD1<ref>https://www.discogs.com/Madonna-What-It-Feels-Like-For-A-Girl/release/35525</ref>\n# \"What It Feels Like for a Girl (Radio Edit)\" \u2013 4:43\n# \"What It Feels Like for a Girl (Tracy Young Cool Out Radio Mix)\" \u2013 4:45\n# \"What It Feels Like for a Girl (Calderone & Quayle Dark Side Mix)\" \u2013 6:42\n# \"What It Feels Like for a Girl (Tracy Young Club Mix)\" \u2013 8:45\n\n;EU CD2<ref>https://www.discogs.com/Madonna-What-It-Feels-Like-For-A-Girl/release/35526</ref>\n# \"What It Feels Like for a Girl (Album Version)\" \u2013 4:43\n# \"What It Feels Like for a Girl (Above & Beyond 12\" Club Mix)\" \u2013 7:27\n# \"What It Feels Like for a Girl (Paul Oakenfold Perfecto Mix)\" \u2013 7:18\n# \"What It Feels Like for a Girl (Richard Vission Velvet Masta Mix)\" \u2013 8:08\n\n==Remixes==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;[[Thunderpuss]] Mixes\n* \"What It Feels Like for a Girl (Thunderpuss Anthem)\" \u2013 11:18\n* \"What It Feels Like for a Girl (Thunderdub)\" \u2013 11:05\n* \"What It Feels Like for a Girl (Tribe-A-Pella)\" \u2013 8:35\n;[[Above & Beyond (group)|Above & Beyond]] Mixes\n* \"What It Feels Like for a Girl (Above & Beyond 12\" Club Mix)\" \u2013 7:27\n* \"What It Feels Like for a Girl (Above & Beyond Radio Edit)\" \u2013 3:45\n;[[Tracy Young]] Mixes\n* \"What It Feels Like for a Girl (Tracy Young Club Mix)\" \u2013 8:45\n* \"What It Feels Like for a Girl (Tracy Young Cool Out Radio Mix)\" \u2013 4:45 \n;[[Victor Calderone|Calderone]] & Mac Quayle Mix\n* \"What It Feels Like for a Girl (Calderone & Quayle Dark Side Mix)\" \u2013 6:42 {{col-2}}\n;[[Richard \"Humpty\" Vission]] Mixes\n* \"What It Feels Like for a Girl (Richard Vission Velvet Masta Mix)\" \u2013 8:08 \n* \"What It Feels Like for a Girl (Richard Vission Velvet